The native folk music Mozambique has been highly influenced Portuguese forms The most popular style modern dance music marrabenta Mozambican music also influenced another Lusophone music Brazil like maxixe its name derived from Maxixe Mozambique and Cuban music like Mozambique Culture was integral part the struggle for independence which began 1964 Leaders the independence movement used cultural solidarity gain support from the common people while the Portuguese colonialists promoted their own culture the time independence came 1975 Mozambican bands had abandoned their previous attempts Europeanstyle music and began forging new forms based out local folk styles and the new African popular music coming from Zaire Zimbabwe Tanzania Zambia and South Africa 1978 the Ministry Education and Culture organized National Dance Festival that involved more than half million people and led the creation numerous organizations and festivals promoting Mozambican music The Chopi people the coastal Inhambane Province are known for unique kind xylophone called mbila timbila and the style music played with which believed the most sophisticated method composition yet found among preliterate peoples Ensembles consist around ten xylophones four sizes and accompany ceremonial dances with long compositions called ngomi which consist overture and ten movements different tempos and styles The ensemble leader serves poet composer conductor and performer creating text improvising melody partially based the features the Chopis tone language and composing second countrapuntal line The musicians the ensemble partially improvise their parts according style instrumental idiom and the leaders indications The composer then consults with the choreographer the ceremony and adjustments are made Nettl 1956 p1819 Marrabenta the bestknown form music from Mozambique urban origin and meant for dancing Marrabenta was born fusion imported European music played improvised materials The word marrabenta derives from the Portuguese rebentar arrabentar the local vernacular meaning break reference cheap guitar strings that snapped quickly Instruments were fashioned out tin cans and pieces wood Lyrics were usually local languages and included songs social criticism well love Additionally there are songs whose lyrics are Portuguese the official language Mozambique for nationwide and international promotion the songs other CPLP nations The late 1970s saw tremendous innovation marrabenta 1001 Music Productions recorded artists and staged large concerts The compilation album Amanhecer was released followed more such LPs under the title Ngoma The most influential early marrabenta performer was Fany Pfumo whose fame began after the success Loko kumbuka Jorgina recorded South Africa HMV and later incorporated South African kwela into his music The group Orchestra Marrabenta Star Moambique formed 1979 led longtime performer Wazimbo The group toured Europe and other parts the world and soon brought international recognition marrabenta Many the most popular musicians modern Mozambique spent time with Orchestra Marrabenta Star Moambique including Stewart Sukuma Chico Antnio Bow Neyma Jos Mucavel and Mingas while other popular bands include Ghorwane Pandza the newest and mostpopular style Mozambican music credited invented NStar Ziqo and Ardiles Maputo Pandza especially popular amongst Mozambican youths and mix Marrabenta and Ragga The roots Pandza originate from Marrabenta but Pandza has more faster tempo with major influences from Ragga and some Hip Hop Most Pandza mostly song Portuguese and the Shangana language from Maputo and its lyrics most the time elaborate the social daily lifestyles young Mozambicans The most notable Pandza singers Mozambique today include Lizha James Ziqo Ardiles Nstar Kuka Roger Denny Junior Czer Boss 